items.abstract: <jats:p>Changes of the elemental composition due to laser surface cleaning of a naturally crusted historical sandstone were investigated by means of the SEM/EDX technique. Data obtained for stone samples prior to and after laser irradiation were compared with those for noncrusted, reference ones. It has been observed that the crust removal resulting from ablative cleaning was accompanied by a decrease of the partial content of elements Al, S, K, Ca, and Mg in the range of 60–80<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>%</mml:mi></mml:math>of their initial value recorded for the noncleaned, crust-covered stone surface. In the stone layer just under the crust coverage, a structure characterized by intergranular spaces between the<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>SiO</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math>grains being the main sandstone component filled with degraded binder was observed. From the coincidence of the binder destruction and chemical composition of the crust, the stone surface destruction due to the long-term interaction of environmental pollution was deduced. The spatial distributions of individual elements obtained by mapping after laser irradiation indicated that besides<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>SiO</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math>the content of elemental components in the sandstone surface layer decreased by 50<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>%</mml:mi></mml:math>, whereas for Fe with the initial content of 4<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>%</mml:mi></mml:math>and other surface remnants: P, Ti, Zn, and Cl—all below 1<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>%</mml:mi></mml:math>, insignificant changes were only revealed. It was concluded in agreement with the literature that surface cleaning by means of the 1064 nm laser does not cause removal of iron from the sandstone surface.</jats:p>
title: Observation of the Laser Cleaning Effect on the Gotland Sandstone Elemental Composition
